misconceptions.conceptual_gap:
In Java, an 'else' is always paired with the closest preceding 'if' that does not already have an 'else' (the 'dangling else' rule), regardless of indentation or how the programmer conceptually groups conditions. Without braces, the structure is:

if (n >= 90) { ... }
else if (n >= 80) { ... }
else if (n >= 70) { ... }
else {
    if (n >= 60) {
        if (n >= 65) { ... }
        else { ... }  // this else belongs to 'if (n >= 65)'
    }
}

So the 'else' on line 16 runs when 'n >= 65' is false *but* 'n >= 60' is true (i.e., 60–64), not when 'n < 60'. For n < 60, the inner 'if (n >= 60)' is skipped entirely and nothing prints at all. The student’s mental model is driven by indentation and intended meaning ("this else is the F case") rather than by the actual syntactic binding rules that Java uses to match each 'else' with a specific 'if'.
